EDITORIAL

Bush slight on regrets

in final televised address

President George W Bush

-delivered his ﬁnal televised ad— I

dress last night, outlining the
successes and even hinting at
some mistakes of his eight—year
presidency — a presidency that
will be remembered for leav-
ing the United States in one of
the most tumultuous periods of
economic and international in-
stability in recent history.

Bush spent most of the ad—
dress defending his foreign
policy record, emphasizing the
importance of his anti—terrorist
and national security efforts fol-
lowing the Sept. 11 attacks. He
praised Afghanistan as a “young
democracy” and Iraq as an “Arab
democracy. in the heart of the
Middle East and a friend to the
United States.”

For a president currently
plagued by‘ one of the worst
economies in the last century,
two wars and a 34 percent ap-
proval rating, Bush was sur-
prisingly short on regrets last
night, only stating that though
there were things he would have
“done differently if given the
chance,” he “always acted with
the best interests of our country
in mind.”

Bush’s persistent defense of
his administration was not sur-
prising. The president has always
prided himself on his.abi_lity to
make decisions and stick with
them, asserting last night that
though many may disagree with
his decisions, “they can agree,
that he was able to make the
tough decisions.” ’

This one statement might
have been one of the most tell-
ing remarks from Bush’s farewell
address. _ - '

Throughout his tenure, Bush

has made and stuck by decisions
that have had far-reaching effects
for both U.S. and foreign citizens
— even after it became clear that
some of these decisions were
made with faulty intelligence and
poor planning.

Though it is important for a
president to stand by his deci-
sions, Bush’s unwavering posi-

tions on Iraq, interrogation,

education and the environment

ultimately exposed a leader who
was unable to make thoughtful
decisions or reflect on changing
intelligence, international devel-
opments and public opinion.

For someone who claims to
act with the American public’s
interest in mind, Bush has con-
sistently displayed little regard
for the opinions of the Ameri-
can public. '

Throughout Bush’s address, it
became difﬁcult to tell whether
the president’s ardent defense
rose from an ongoing belief in
his decisions and record, or from
a last-ditch effort at preserving
his legacy. Whatever his motiva-
tions, Bush is clearly leaving the
White House-with few regrets.

Whether these reﬂections
change m the years to come, his
current unwillingness to accept
defeat suggests a certain imma-
turity in Bush. '

A strong leader would be
capable of acknowledging his
mistakes and insecurities,‘ reﬂect

on what he might have done dif-

ferently and speak humbly of his

. faults. '

We hope in the months and
years to come, the country will
rebound and recover from the
last eight years and move toward
a future of economic prosperity
and global tolerance. A

