alyptic with joy. I sawa ﬁreman

tending to a couch blaze only to ’

have his visor yanked up by an in-
toxicated co—ed, the two of whom

then proceeded to make out with '

each other. It was beautiful.
If the Steelers meet the Eagles

in the Super Bowl, I have no doubt I

that the public display that ensues,
regardless of outcome, will effort-
lessly eclipse the events of Feb. 5,
2006. While Pittsburgh is through
and through a Steelers town, Oak-

land ﬁnds itself a house divided, ‘

suffused with the Philly fandom
of students from the East.

When the fourth quarter ends,
the streets of our quaint campus
will be set alive with sectarian vio-
lence, the likes of which I can only
conceive in “Gangs of New Yor ”
imagery. if

I foresee a wave of black crash-
ing with a wave of green and the
rest is in slow motion. 1, for one,
cannot wait.

_ However, - drunk on such
dreams, I begin to wonder, “Why
is Pittsburgh so very inclined to
rioting.” The Steelers, West Vir-
ginia games, President—elect Ba-
rack Obama —— it seems like the
city needs very little provocation
to send itself into marches, chants,

car ﬂipping and indecent expo’-
sure.

The answer might be as simple.

as, “We have a lot of college stu-
dents and a lot of bars.” The con-
vergence of these twain is gener-
ally disorderly conduct. However,
a lot of cities have alcohol and
young adults. What makes Pitts-
burgh special? H

I suggest that the catalyst for
the steel city’s aping of L.A. is its
anachronistic workman’s spirit.
When Pittsburgh was thriving un-
der the sooty cloud of its mills and
the Steelers were a young team, a
ﬁerce bond between the workers

and the team was forged. Pitts- ,

burgh sports became a source
of diversion for the labor—weary
populace. Before long, the Steel-
ers were the lifeblood of the town.
You all know the story.
